<p>
  We help teams write meaningful accessibility requirements into procurement documents and assess how well vendor products actually meet those requirements.
</p>

<h2>How we help</h2>
<ul class="list-disc mb-300">
  <li class="mb-75">Writing accessibility criteria for Statements of Work (SOWs), Requests for Proposals (RFPs), and Requests for Information (RFIs)</li>
  <li class="mb-75">Reviewing vendor-supplied Accessibility Conformance Reports (ACRs) and VPAT documents</li>
  <li class="mb-75">Testing vendor products against WCAG 2.1 AA as part of evaluation</li>
  <li>Advising on contractual obligations and remediation timelines</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>
  Government of Canada procurement requirements include accessibility. Including clear, testable accessibility criteria in contracts protects both public servants and members of the public who use the products your department acquires.
</p>

<h2>Request procurement guidance</h2>
<p>
  Contact us at <a href="mailto:aaact-aatia@ssc-spc.gc.ca">aaact-aatia@ssc-spc.gc.ca</a> as early in the procurement process as possible. We can help at any stage, but earlier involvement leads to better outcomes.
</p>

